Ford Motor Company, like many other businesses, faced significant challenges during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020. Here is an overview of Ford's revenue, profits, and costs during this period:

Revenue:
In 2020, Ford's revenue was $127.1 billion, which represents a decrease of approximately 18% compared to the previous year. This decline was primarily due to lower vehicle sales and production volumes resulting from pandemic-related disruptions.

Profits:
Ford reported a net loss of $2.8 billion in 2020, which was a significant decline from the $47 million profit it reported in 2019. This loss was due to the impact of the pandemic, as well as costs associated with restructuring and other initiatives aimed at improving the company's financial performance.

Costs:
Ford faced a number of costs related to the pandemic in 2020, including expenses related to plant shutdowns, supply chain disruptions, and employee health and safety measures. In addition, the company incurred costs related to restructuring and other initiatives aimed at improving its financial position.

Despite these challenges, Ford remained focused on executing its long-term strategy, which includes a strong emphasis on electric and autonomous vehicles, as well as an ongoing commitment to sustainable business practices. The company has announced plans to invest more than $22 billion in electric vehicle development by 2025 and expects to have more than 40% of its global vehicle volume to be fully electric by 2030.